video

First, determine the mean of the sample.

\[\bar{x} = \frac{\sum \mathbf{x}}{n} =28 \]

Determine the squared deviations (squared distances from \(\bar{x}\)).

\[i\] \[\mathbf{x}\] deviations = \(\mathbf{x}-\bar{x}\) SqrDev = \((\mathbf{x}-\bar{x})^2\)
1 27 -1 1
2 24 -4 16
3 31 3 9
4 30 2 4
5 30 2 4
6 30 2 4
7 26 -2 4
8 30 2 4
9 28 0 0
10 24 -4 16

Determine the unbiased sample variance by summing the squared deviations and dividing the sum by \(n-1\).

\[s^2 = \frac{\sum (\mathbf{x}-\bar{x})^2}{n-1} = \frac{62}{10-1} = 6.8888889 \]

Determine the corrected sample standard deviation by taking the square root of the unbiased sample variance.

\[s=\sqrt{s^2}=\sqrt{6.8888889}=2.6246693\]

spreadsheet

You can do this with a spreadsheet.


And, actually, you can skip a lot of work by using the STDEV function.

R

You can do this with R

x = read.csv("get_SD.csv")$x
sd(x)
## [1] 2.624669

You could also do it the long way.

x = read.csv("get_SD.csv")$x
n = length(x)
xbar = mean(x)
deviations = x-xbar
sqrdev = deviations^2
VAR = sum(sqrdev)/(n-1)
SD = sqrt(VAR)
SD
## [1] 2.624669
